Legal record[edit]
Bribery allegations[edit]
In December 2007, the Securities and Exchange Commission levied charges against former chairman and CEO Robert Philip for allegedly violating bribery laws as part of the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act in relation to dealings with Chinese steel mills.[11] In 2008, Tamara Lundgren became the chief executive officer with John Carter leaving that position to become the chairman of the board.[12][13]
Family control and supermajority voting shares[edit]
The Schnitzer family had maintained control of the corporation through supermajority voting rights until January 2010, when family members had sold off stock and dropped their stake in the company to less than 20 percent.[3]
